tes the textures of national-identity formation, Constitutive Visions places petitions from indigenous laborers alongside oil paintings, overlays woodblock illustrations with legislative debates, and analyzes Ecuador’s nineteen constitutions in light of landscape painting. Taken together, these juxtapositions make sense of the contradictions that sustained and unsettled the postcolonial nation-state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuadorxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuadorxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aNational characteristics, EcuadorianxHistoryy19th century. 0aNational characteristics, EcuadorianxHistoryy20th century. 0aRhetoriczEcuadorxHistoryy19th century. 0aRhetoriczEcuadorxHistoryy20th century. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh  aChrista J. Olson.  aIdentity in Republican Ecuador.  aIndigeneity and Commonplaces of Nationa.  aRhetoric and Democratic Deliberation Series.  ahistory Constitutive Visions.  arhetoric indigeneity.  avisual culture Ecuador.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271062549?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271062549423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271062549/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK